            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": ""
        },
        {
            "text": "G6PD deficiency can be a challenge during the COVID-19 pandemic. The above-cited ex vivo study has found that \u03b1-lipoic acid can attenuate the vulnerability of G6PD-deficient cells [3] .",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 180,
                    "end": 183,
                    "text": "[3]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF2"
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": ""
        },
        {
            "text": "Thus, \u03b1-lipoic acid has been proposed as a treatment option for infection with severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2) that causes COVID-19 [4] .",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 161,
                    "end": 164,
                    "text": "[4]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF3"
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": ""
        },
        {
            "text": "Hydroxychloroquine has been proposed as a treatment for COVID-19 and clinical trials have been started evaluating this proposal. Hydroxychloroquine has oxidative properties that could decrease glutathione levels and may cause severe hemolysis in G6PD-deficient patients [5] . If hydroxychloroquine is found to be the silver bullet for COVID-19, then this may be a big challenge in treating COVID-19 in G6PD-deficient patients. Accordingly, it is prudent to use additional precautionary measures to prevent COVID-19 from reaching G6PD-deficient individuals.",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 270,
                    "end": 273,
                    "text": "[5]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF4"
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
